Below is a single self-contained HTML file that demonstrates a shared state concurrency bug using a progress bar. The file includes:

- **Buggy Implementation**: Multiple concurrent tasks (simulated using `setTimeout` and Promises) that update a shared percentage variable without synchronization. This can lead to issues like incorrect values (e.g., skipping percentages), exceeding 100%, or inconsistent results due to race conditions. In JavaScript's single-threaded event loop, these issues arise because asynchronous tasks can interleave their execution, causing one task to read an outdated value before another writes.

- **Corrected Implementation**: The same tasks are run, but updates are synchronized using a simple sequential approach (e.g., chaining promises with `await`). This ensures that only one task modifies the shared state at a time, preventing race conditions.

The page is divided into two sections, each with:
- A progress bar (using HTML and CSS for simplicity).
- A button to start the tasks.
- An explanation of the problem or fix.

This demo uses random delays to simulate real-world concurrency, so you might need to run it multiple times to see the buggy behavior clearly.

Here's the full HTML file:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Shared State Concurrency Bug Demo</title>
    <style>
        /* CSS for styling the page and progress bars */
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 20px;
        }
        h1, h2 {
            color: #333;
        }
        .section {
            margin-bottom: 40px;
            border: 1px solid #ddd;
            padding: 20px;
            border-radius: 8px;
        }
        .progress-bar {
            width: 100%;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 4px;
            overflow: hidden;
        }
        .progress-fill {
            height: 20px;
            background-color: #4CAF50; /* Green for progress */
            width: 0%; /* Starts at 0% */
            transition: width 0.2s ease-in-out; /* Smooth animation */
        }
        button {
            padding: 10px 15px;
            background-color: #007BFF;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 4px;
            cursor: pointer;
            margin-top: 10px;
        }
        button:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }
        .explanation {
            background-color: #f9f9f9;
            padding: 10px;
            border: 1px solid #e0e0e0;
            border-radius: 4px;
            margin-top: 10px;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Shared State Concurrency Bug Demo</h1>
    <p>This demo shows a shared state concurrency issue in JavaScript. Five tasks each try to add 20% to a shared progress variable (targeting 100%). In the buggy version, unsynchronized updates can cause errors like skipping values or exceeding 100%. The corrected version fixes this with synchronization.</p>

    <div class="section">
        <h2>Buggy Implementation</h2>
        <p class="explanation">
            <strong>Problem Explanation:</strong> Here, multiple asynchronous tasks (using <code>setTimeout</code> and Promises) access and update a shared percentage variable without coordination. This leads to a race condition: one task might read the current value, then another task updates it before the first one writes back, resulting in lost updates, skipped percentages, or values exceeding 100%. For example, if two tasks both read 0 and add 20, the final value might only be 20 instead of 40.
        </p>
        <div id="buggy-progress-bar" class="progress-bar">
            <div id="buggy-progress-fill" class="progress-fill"></div>
        </div>
        <p>Current Buggy Percentage: <span id="buggy-percentage-display">0%</span></p>
        <button id="buggy-button">Start Buggy Tasks</button>
    </div>

    <div class="section">
        <h2>Corrected Implementation</h2>
        <p class="explanation">
            <strong>Fix Explanation:</strong> In this version, updates are synchronized by running tasks sequentially using <code>async/await</code> and Promises. This ensures that only one task modifies the shared state at a time, avoiding race conditions. By chaining the tasks, we prevent interleaved access, so the percentage updates correctly without skipping values or exceeding 100%.
        </p>
        <div id="corrected-progress-bar" class="progress-bar">
            <div id="corrected-progress-fill" class="progress-fill"></div>
        </div>
        <p>Current Corrected Percentage: <span id="corrected-percentage-display">0%</span></p>
        <button id="corrected-button">Start Corrected Tasks</button>
    </div>

    <script>
        // Shared variables for each implementation
        let buggyPercentage = 0;  // Shared state for buggy demo
        let correctedPercentage = 0;  // Shared state for corrected demo

        // Function to update the buggy progress bar and display
        function updateBuggyBar() {
            document.getElementById('buggy-progress-fill').style.width = buggyPercentage + '%';
            document.getElementById('buggy-percentage-display').textContent = buggyPercentage + '%';
        }

        // Function to update the corrected progress bar and display
        function updateCorrectedBar() {
            document.getElementById('corrected-progress-fill').style.width = correctedPercentage + '%';
            document.getElementById('corrected-percentage-display').textContent = correctedPercentage + '%';
        }

        // Buggy implementation: Unsynchronized updates
        function startBuggyTasks() {
            buggyPercentage = 0;  // Reset
            updateBuggyBar();  // Reset the bar

            // Launch 5 concurrent tasks
            for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
                // Use setTimeout for asynchronous delay and Promise for additional concurrency simulation
                setTimeout(() => {
                    new Promise(resolve => {
                        setTimeout(() => {
                            let current = buggyPercentage;  // Read the current value
                            // Simulate a delay in processing (e.g., race condition opportunity)
                            setTimeout(() => {
                                buggyPercentage = current + 20;  // Add 20% (unsynchronized)
                                if (buggyPercentage > 100) buggyPercentage = 100;  // Cap at 100%
                                updateBuggyBar();  // Update the UI
                                console.log('Buggy task ' + i + ' updated percentage to:', buggyPercentage);
                                resolve();
                            }, Math.random() * 500);  // Random short delay to exacerbate the issue
                        }, Math.random() * 1000);  // Random initial delay
                    });
                }, Math.random() * 500);  // Even more randomness
            }
        }

        // Corrected implementation: Synchronized updates
        async function startCorrectedTasks() {
            correctedPercentage = 0;  // Reset
            updateCorrectedBar();  // Reset the bar

            for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
                // Wait for a random delay (simulating concurrency), then update sequentially
                await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, Math.random() * 1000));
                correctedPercentage += 20;  // Add 20% in a synchronized manner
                if (correctedPercentage > 100) correctedPercentage = 100;  // Cap at 100%
                updateCorrectedBar();  // Update the UI
                console.log('Corrected task ' + i + ' updated percentage to:', correctedPercentage);
            }
        }

        // Add event listeners for the buttons
        document.getElementById('buggy-button').addEventListener('click', startBuggyTasks);
        document.getElementById('corrected-button').addEventListener('click', startCorrectedTasks);
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### How to Use This File:
1. Save the code to a file with a `.html` extension (e.g., `concurrency-demo.html`).
2. Open the file in a web browser.
3. Click the "Start Buggy Tasks" button to see the buggy behavior. You might observe the progress bar jumping erratically, skipping values (e.g., going from 20% to 60% instead of 40%), or exceeding 100% due to race conditions.
4. Click the "Start Corrected Tasks" button to see the fixed behavior. The progress bar should increment smoothly to 100% without issues.

### Key Takeaways:
- **Shared State Problem**: In the buggy version, the shared variable (`buggyPercentage`) is accessed and modified by multiple tasks concurrently. JavaScript's event loop processes these tasks one at a time, but the lack of synchronization means that tasks can "step on each other's toes," leading to inconsistent results.
- **Fix**: In the corrected version, we use `async/await` to sequence the updates, effectively creating a "lock" by ensuring tasks wait for the previous one to complete. This is a simple way to handle shared state in JavaScript without needing external libraries.

