<body>
    <h1>Shared State Concurrency Bug Demonstration</h1>
    <p>This demo shows a progress bar updated by multiple concurrent tasks. The left side has a buggy implementation that can lead to incorrect results due to race conditions on a shared state variable. The right side has a corrected version that fixes the issue.</p>

    <div class="container">
        <div class="section" id="buggy-section">
            <h2>Buggy Implementation</h2>
            <div class="progress-bar">
                <div id="buggy-progress-fill" class="progress-bar-fill"></div>
            </div>
            <p>Current Progress: <span id="buggy-progress-text">0%</span></p>
            <button id="buggy-start-button">Start Buggy Simulation</button>
            <div class="explanation">
                <h3>Explanation of the Problem:</h3>
                <p>In this version, multiple tasks concurrently update a shared <code>progress</code> variable using <code>setTimeout</code> and <code>Promise</code>. Due to race conditions, tasks might read the same value of <code>progress</code>, add to it, and write back, overwriting each other's changes. This can result in skipped percentages, incorrect values, or the progress exceeding 100% (e.g., if two tasks both add 10 to 90, it might end up at 100 instead of 110, or jump erratically).</p>
            </div>
